SIMPLE: tradition
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tradition
<hw>Tra*di"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>tradicioun</ets>, L. <ets>traditio</ets>, from <ets>tradere</ets>
to give up, transmit. See <er>Treason</er>, <er>Traitor</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of delivering into the hands of another;
delivery.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A deed takes effect only from the
<xex>tradition</xex> or delivery.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The unwritten or oral delivery of information,
opinions, doctrines, practices, rites, and customs, from father to son,
or from ancestors to posterity; the transmission of any knowledge,
opinions, or practice, from forefathers to descendants by oral
communication, without written memorials.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, that which is transmitted orally from father
to son, or from ancestors to posterity; knowledge or belief transmitted
without the aid of written memorials; custom or practice long
observed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will you mock at an ancient <qex>tradition</qex> begun upon an
honorable respect?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Naught but <qex>tradition</qex> remains of the beautiful village
of Grand-Pr⟦eacute⟧.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An unwritten code
of law represented to have been given by God to Moses on
Sinai.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Making the word of God of none effect through your
<qex>tradition</qex>, which ye have delivered.</q> <rj><qau>Mark vii.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>That body of doctrine and discipline, or any
article thereof, supposed to have been put forth by Christ or his
apostles, and not committed to writing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stand fast, and hold the <qex>traditions</qex> which ye have been
taught, whether by word or our epistle.</q> <rj><qau>2 Thess. ii.
15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tradition Sunday</b></col> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld>, <cd>Palm
Sunday; -- so called because the creed was then taught to candidates for
baptism at Easter.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tradition</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tradition
<hw>Tra*di"tion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To transmit by way of
tradition; to hand down.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The following story is . . . <qex>traditioned</qex> with very much
credit amongst our English Catholics.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traditional</ent>⟦br⟧
